english:
  title: Memorial on the Strategic Geography of the Five Fortresses
  author: Kim Jong-seo
  language: eng
  text: "Your servant humbly submits that when virtue and majesty spread wide, establishing kingdoms of a hundred leagues is not uncommon, yet none surpassed the Duke of Zhou; when military force is wielded recklessly to expand territory by a thousand leagues, this too is not rare, yet none exceeded the Han Emperor Wu. There are also those weak and declining rulers who lose ground daily—hardly worth mentioning. Yet there is a difference in the way: those who build kingdoms through virtue find them easy to gain but hard to lose, while those who expand through force find them hard to gain but easy to lose. This is one endeavor, yet the principle differs.\n\nKoguryeo's founder unified the Three Han through military prowess, yet his influence did not extend to the northern reaches—he merely made the Iron Ridge his boundary. In the reign of King Sejong, strategic minds deployed their craft, luring and crushing the barbarians, establishing nine fortified cities. Yet these were gained and lost in turn. Our Great Progenitor, endowed with heaven-sent sagacity and martial virtue, rising from the northern frontier, came to possess the great realm. Southeastward to the sea, northwestward to the Yalu, northeastward to the Tumen—he established seven provinces: Kong, Kyong, Kil, Tan, Ch'ong, Hong, and Ham. This was truly an unparalleled achievement in the history of the Eastern Kingdom's expansion. Our Taejong, inheriting the throne, refined governance through moral cultivation. After long refinement, the barbarians became civilized folk, their customs transformed toward virtue. The realm was maintained in stability, none dared challenge it.\n\nYet as years of peace accumulated, frontier commanders grew lax. North of Kyongson fell into bandit territory. Taejong, moved with concern, temporarily placed Kyongwon at Pugo, subtly suggesting the intention to restore what was lost. The driving back of barbarians and recovery of territory awaits the present sage.\n\nFormer courtiers submitted proposals: \"If Kyongwon is moved to Yongson, the northern approach will be properly arranged, and the people's suffering will entirely cease.\" Yet Your Majesty deemed the land guarded by our ancestors, though but a span or inch, sacred and not to be abandoned. You held firm against the collective counsel. Later the proposal arose again, clamorous and unceasing. Thus you sent your humble servant to consult with great ministers, and established the Ningbuk Fortress at Sokm'ak to fix the boundaries.\n\nYour servant, stationed long in the north, has seen and heard much. Neither Pugo nor Sokm'ak are fit for boundaries; Yongson itself is no gatehouse. Those who argue say: \"Yongson is like the Hanguguan Pass of Ch'in—unmatched in its peril. If we guard it there, the northern tribes dare not raid us with malice, and our people can sleep peacefully in their beds.\" This is greatly mistaken. Without water to obstruct, how establish defense? Without mountains to rest upon, how secure fortification? This place is truly the \"land of dispersal and four-sided combat.\" \n\nIf the four settlements' vital points are to be strengthened, they should be made great fortresses serving as the commander's seat and support for the four towns—this makes sense. Yet if Yongson becomes the boundary as some propose, one cannot escape invasion's threat. Then later counselors will propose the Mach'on Ridge, and when that fails, they will say the Iron Ridge. The former dynasty's example teaches this lesson.\n\nYour servant has heard: All emperors value the land of their dynasty's founding. Han cherished Fengpei; Tang cherished Jingyang. If we abandon our ancestors' territory and do not guard it, if we forget our founding place and do not recover it—can we speak of worthy succession? Can we claim to have advanced the great work of our forebears?\n\nMoreover, taking Yongson as boundary contains one injustice and two disadvantages: reducing ancestral land is the injustice; lacking mountain and water defenses and lacking garrison convenience are the two disadvantages. Taking the Tumen as boundary contains one great justice and two great advantages: recovering the founder's realm is the justice; relying on the great river's peril and having garrison convenience are the two advantages. Thus those who would make Yongson the limit simply have not pondered this fully.\n\nHeaven favors the righteous; the guilty barbarians fled of themselves. The sage, seizing the moment, moved no troops and harmed no people, yet recovered the ancient territory and established four settlements. This is truly to advance worthily what ancestors began, adding lustre to their legacy.\n\nYour servant has heard: \"The builder of great enterprise disregards small hindrances; the founder of great works does not calculate small harms. When works are vast, hindrances must arise; when undertakings are broad, harms must follow. This is not unique to our time—it has been so since ancient days.\" The establishing of four settlements is not from love of grandiosity but from recovering ancestral land—no greater work exists. It is to inherit the royal enterprise—no weightier duty exists. Why then fear small hindrances or worry over small harms? \n\nThough the snow of the first year was great, livestock did not perish greatly. Though the plague of the next year was severe, people did not die in great numbers. If the critics spoke truth, where would farming oxen and war horses come from? Yet military strength and reserves have not diminished. This exaggeration is plain without need of wise judgment.\n\nAs for last year's calamities: though severe, they pale beside the deaths at Hungbu, the military collapse under Seungwu, or the great defeat at Yongson. Nine years of floods did not diminish the virtue of Yao and Tang; fifty thousand Xiongnu and forty thousand Turks could not harm the great deeds of Han and Tang. Our calamity lasted but one year; the raiders number but thousands. Why such worry and dread?\n\nYour servant has heard that ancient heroes built the ten-thousand-li walls against barbarians and thousand-li dikes against rivers, conscripting people for ten long years—excessive, truly. Yet posterity reaped the benefit. Our realm, bordered by Mohe in the north, has suffered countless invasions. From the former dynasty to now, this threat persists. Thus fortification and military training here should exceed other regions a hundredfold. Though we build one city yearly without end, what injustice is there? Under the former boundary at Pugo, not even several feet of walls stood. If the frontier settlement was thus, how much more the southern territories? \n\nReflecting now, the frontier strategy was gravely mistaken; no wonder the Chinese laugh. Yet Your Majesty, moved with concern, heeded your counselors. The people, mustered forth, built first Hwaeryong, then Kyongwon—the labor finished within its season, the work completed. How much more Kaps'an and Kyonghung, which can fortify themselves with solid walls? The northern anxiety has diminished by seven or eight parts in ten.\n\nYour servant has heard: When Yin attacked the Kingdom of Ghosts, it took three years. Zhou soldiers on garrison duty said, \"Three years I have not seen home,\" and \"When shall I return?\" Even the people of Yin and Zhou could not escape long garrison duty. Since then barbarians grew bolder and garrison duty more bitter. Seeing the poem \"Returning with whitened head, then back to garrison duty,\" we understand. This afflicted not only China but our former dynasty too. First they made the Iron Ridge the gate, then the Double Fortress the boundary, sending soldiers from lower routes to garrison there. Some grew old in service without returning home—even fathers and sons could not recognize each other. The distance and length of service are evident. Compared to today, heaven and earth differ!\n\nYour servant has heard: Moving settlements is a grave matter, breeding resentment and harming harmony—ancient sages deeply feared this. How much more moving peaceful folk to lands of wolves and tigers? Few would not resent it. Yet your sage calculation is wondrous: without flogging a single official or punishing a single subject, tens of thousands assembled at the new lands within a month. A great work easily accomplished, a new settlement eternally established—utterly unlike the gaining and losing of before.\n\nUnexpectedly, shallow folk, grasping at the great snow of the first year and great plague of the next, spread false rumors and swayed the people's hearts, nearly ruining the great work and losing the past achievement. Fortunately, Your Majesty's clear judgment silenced false talk and settled people's hearts. Moreover, spreading benevolence widely—giving clothes to the cold, food to the hungry—the people, though burdened by labor, forgot their toil; soldiers, though weary of garrison duty, forgot their hardship. An ancient sage said, \"If the people's suffering does not come from above's command, they harbor righteous anger,\" and \"Using joy to command the people, they forget their labor\"—this is precisely it.\n\nToday's establishing of four settlements is solely to make them barriers for the north. Today's building of walls is solely to solidify these barriers. Today's garrison duty is also to repel raiders and bring peace to our people. Thus today's work is not optional but essential. It is not reckless use of the people's strength, nor the wasteful display of military might. Indeed, though the people are ignorant, how could they not understand this purpose? A certain commoner told your servant: \"Hwaeryong and Kyongwon now have walls. Only Chongson and Yongson remain to be built. Once these two are complete, we shall have no worries.\" This speaks truth. From this, the hearts of other folk are manifest.\n\nLast year's calamity at Kyongwon was dire, yet the people showed no fear. The scattered gathered, the fled returned, took up farming, settled in livelihood—no different from peaceful days. Observing today's work, we may expect their sacrifice unto death in future. Some, unable to contain their fervor, will charge the foe themselves, beheading raiders. Examining past patterns, we may expect their willingness to lay down their lives for their lord. From Kyongwon alone, we may infer the hearts of the three other settlements' soldiers and people.\n\nYour servant, long stationed in the north, knows the barbarians' nature well. Even between father and son, brother and brother, when greed arises, they slay and harm each other as enemies. Though one spent a thousand gold daily, binding their hearts would be difficult. Winning them through profit, when profit ceases, their malice returns. The superior way is to show benevolence outwardly while preparing defense within. Thus our strength grows naturally and theirs weakens naturally. With our growing strength, seizing their weakness, we achieve our aims.\n\nYour servant's urgency in building walls, preparing arms, training soldiers, and storing provisions stems from this. When walls are solid, arms are sturdy, soldiers trained, the four fortresses' people can defend themselves and fight without awaiting outside help. Whether the barbarians' invasions cease forever and their hearts submit eternally is hard to predict.\n\nYour servant further reflects: When first settling, with mere feet-high palisades, the people could still hold firm. How much more now with stone walls built? What fear remains for self-defense? The people had no stores, the state no reserves, yet famine brought no starvation. Now harvests come yearly—the people have surplus grain, the state has reserves. Why fear depletion? The state demands no tax, the people contribute nothing. How could resources exhaust? The people's hearts are settled, fugitives decline daily. How could people vanish? Once Chongson's walls complete, the people's strength will rest. Yongson is not urgent—it need not be hastened when resources permit.\n\nYour servant has heard: \"A virtuous person governing a state, after a hundred years, can eliminate cruelty and violence.\" This means even the virtuous cannot claim success before a hundred years. How much less can new settlements, not yet ten years old, be judged? Why rejoice at one success or grieve at one failure?\n\nYour servant humbly begs: Let Your Majesty not seek hasty completion, not value small gains, not calculate small hindrances, not worry over small threats. With time and patience, false rumors will cease naturally, people's hearts will settle naturally, their suffering will fade naturally, their resentments will end naturally, their food will suffice naturally, military strength will grow naturally, raiders will submit naturally, and the new settlements will endure eternally.\n\nYet what your servant says may not be wholly believable. Concerning last year's snow, critics claimed all livestock perished, but your servant said otherwise. Concerning next year's plague, critics claimed people nearly all died, but your servant said otherwise. The court deemed them right and your servant wrong, them loyal and your servant self-seeking. Your servant's heart aches boundlessly. Looking now, events leave traces that cannot be hidden. Who is loyal, who self-seeking? Who serves the public, who private interest? These distinctions rest solely on Your Majesty's luminous judgment. Since ancient times, officials building works in outlying regions inevitably face slander and calumny; many could not escape disaster. Yun Kwan of the former dynasty is perhaps one example. Though from a great house with great deeds, he barely escaped this fate. How much more your servant—without even small achievements, without talent for building works, with only failures mounting—how could I not be troubled?"
  footnotes:
    - The 'Five Fortresses' (오진) refers to the four major settlements established in the northern frontier (會寧, 慶源, 鍾城, 龍城) plus their supporting fortress at Ningbuk (寧北鎭).
    - Kim Jong-seo is defending the military frontier policy against critics who complained about the hardships of establishing and maintaining these northern settlements.
    - The reference to Yun Kwan alludes to the historical persecution of this renowned general despite his significant military achievements.
    - 'The ''Three Han'' (三韓) refers to the three ancient Korean kingdoms: Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla.'
